qas.question: What is a "grand" sometimes shortened to?
What is another term other than "large" that means a stack of mutiple thousands?
What is a "C-note" a reference to?
Which note is occasionally called a "yardstick"?
What is another term for "bigface" notes?
What is a "sawbuck" sometimes shortened to?
What is another term other than "sawbuck" that means a stack of multiple thousands?
What is a G-note a reference to?
Which note is occasionally called a largestick?
What is another term for obverse notes?

context: A "grand", sometimes shortened to simply <a0_0>"<b5_0>G<b5_0/>"<a0_0/>, is a common term for the amount of $1,000. The suffix "K" or "k" (from "kilo-") is also commonly used to denote this amount (such as "$10k" to mean $10,000). However, the $1,000 note is no longer in general use. A "large" or <a1_0>"<b6_0>stack<b6_0/>"<a1_0/>, it is usually a reference to a multiple of $1,000 (such as "fifty large" meaning $50,000). The $100 note is nicknamed "Benjamin", "Benji", "Ben", or "Franklin" (after Benjamin Franklin), "C-note" (C being <a2_0><b7_0>the Roman numeral for 100<b7_0/><a2_0/>), "Century note" or "bill" (e.g. "two bills" being $200). The <a3_0><b8_0>$50<b8_0/><a3_0/> note is occasionally called a "yardstick" or a "grant" (after President Ulysses S. Grant, pictured on the obverse). The $20 note is referred to as a "double sawbuck", "Jackson" (after Andrew Jackson), or "double eagle". The $10 note is referred to as a "sawbuck", "ten-spot" or "Hamilton" (after Alexander Hamilton). The $5 note as "Lincoln", "fin", "fiver" or "five-spot". The infrequently-used $2 note is sometimes called "deuce", "Tom", or "Jefferson" (after Thomas Jefferson). The $1 note as a "single" or "buck". The dollar has also been, referred to as a "bone" and "bones" in plural (e.g. "twenty bones" is equal to $20). The newer designs, with portraits displayed in the main body of the obverse rather than in cameo insets upon paper color-coded by denomination, are sometimes referred to as "bigface" notes or "<a4_0><b9_0>Monopoly money<b9_0/><a4_0/>".
